-- Managment for Waste Pipes

Side = "left"
rednet.open("top")

while true do
	id, message = rednet.receive("WASTE_MANAGEMENT")
	if message == "TRUE" then
		redstone.setOutput(Side, true)
	else
		redstone.setOutput(Side, false)
	end
	term.clear()
	term.setCursorPos(1, 1)
	print("Computer: " .. os.getComputerID())
	print("Output: ".. message)
	if icon then
		w,h = term.getSize()
		term.setCursorPos(w, h)
		term.write("*")
	else
		w,h = term.getSize()
		term.setCursorPos(w, h)
		term.write(" ")
	end
	icon = not icon
end

-- Monitoring for Nuclear Waste

Monitor = peripheral.wrap("monitor_3")
Threashhold = 0.8
Tanks = {
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_0",   7},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_1",   8},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_2",   9},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_3",  10},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_4",  11},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_5",  12},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_6",  13},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_7",  14},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_8",  15},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_9",  16},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_10", 17},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_11", 18},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_12", 19},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_13", 20},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_14", 21},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_15", 22},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_16", 23},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_17", 24},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_18", 25},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_19", 26},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_20", 28},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_21", 29},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_22", 30},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_23", 31},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_24", 32},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_25", 33},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_26", 34},
	{"radioactiveWasteBarrel_27", 35},
}
rednet.open("bottom")

while true do
	currentLowestTank = 0
	currentLowestPercentage = 0
	totalPercentage = 0
	for i, tank in pairs(Tanks) do
		 tnk = peripheral.wrap(Tanks[i][1])
		 percentage = tnk.getFilledPercentage()
		 if currentLowestPercentage <= percentage and percentage < Threashhold then
			currentLowestTank = i
			currentLowestPercentage = percentage
			totalPercentage = totalPercentage + percentage
		end
	end
	
	for i, tank in pairs(Tanks) do
		 if currentLowestTank == i then
			rednet.send(Tanks[i][2], "FALSE", "WASTE_MANAGEMENT")
		else
			rednet.send(Tanks[i][2], "TRUE", "WASTE_MANAGEMENT")
		end
	end
	term.clear()
	term.setCursorPos(1, 1)
	term.write("Filled: " .. (totalPercentage/#Tanks)*100 .. "%")
	term.setCursorPos(1, 2)
	term.write("Filling: " .. Tanks[currentLowestTank][1])
	Monitor.clear()
	Monitor.setCursorPos(1, 1)
	Monitor.write("Filled: " .. (totalPercentage/#Tanks)*100 .. "%")
	Monitor.setCursorPos(1, 2)
	Monitor.write("Filling: " .. Tanks[currentLowestTank][1])
	
	if icon then
		w,h = term.getSize()
		term.setCursorPos(w, h)
		term.write("*")
		w,h = Monitor.getSize()
		Monitor.setCursorPos(w, h)
		Monitor.write("*")
	else
		w,h = term.getSize()
		term.setCursorPos(w, h)
		term.write(" ")
		w,h = Monitor.getSize()
		Monitor.setCursorPos(w, h)
		Monitor.write(" ")
	end
	icon = not icon
	os.sleep(0.5)
end

title: transport
content:
function left()
    
    turtle.turnLeft()
    direction = direction - 1
    if direction == 0 then
        direction = 4
    end
    saveDirection()
    
end

function right()
    
    turtle.turnRight()
    direction = direction + 1
    if direction == 5 then
        direction = 1
    end
    saveDirection()
    
end

-----------------------------------------------MAIN-----------------------------------------------------------------------

rednet.open('left')
while true do

id, instruction = rednet.receive()
id, repeats = rednet.receive()
for i = 1, repeats do

    if instruction == 'forward' then
        turtle.forward()
    elseif instruction == 'up' then
        turtle.up()
    elseif instruction == 'down' then 
        if turtle.detectDown() then
            turtle.digDown()
        end
        turtle.down()
    elseif instruction == 'left' then
        left()
    else 
        right()
    end

end

end

title: Minecraft Texture For Roblox Arsenal
content:
-- NOTE this does WORK in some games

        local faces = {"Front", "Back", "Bottom", "Top", "Right", "Left"}
        local materials = {
            {"Wood", "3258599312"}, {"WoodPlanks", "8676581022"},
            {"Brick", "8558400252"}, {"Cobblestone", "5003953441"},
            {"Concrete", "7341687607"}, {"DiamondPlate", "6849247561"},
            {"Fabric", "118776397"}, {"Granite", "4722586771"},
            {"Grass", "4722588177"}, {"Ice", "3823766459"},
            {"Marble", "62967586"}, {"Metal", "62967586"},
            {"Sand", "152572215"}
        }
        
        function texture(ins, id)
            for _, v in pairs(faces) do
                local texture = Instance.new("Texture", ins)
                texture.ZIndex = 2147483647
                texture.Texture = "rbxassetid://" .. id
                texture.Face = Enum.NormalId[v]
                texture.Color3 = ins.Color
                texture.Transparency = ins.Transparency
            end
        end
        
        for _, part in pairs(workspace:GetDescendants()) do
            if part:IsA("BasePart") then
                for _, v in pairs(materials) do
                    if part.Material.Name == v[1] then
                        texture(part, v[2])
                        part.Material = "SmoothPlastic"
                    end
                end
            end
        end

Python from ChatGPT - Print 0 to 4096
content:
# Python program written by ChatGPT to print 
# the numbers from 0 to 4096 in columns.

# Define the range of numbers
start = 0
end = 4096

# Print the column headers
print("Decimal   Binary       Hexadecimal")
print("-" * 32)

# Iterate through the numbers and print them in three columns
for num in range(start, end + 1):
    binary_num = bin(num)[2:]
    hexadecimal_num = hex(num)[2:].upper()
    print(f"{num:7}   {binary_num:12}   {hexadecimal_num}")

The dystopian version of superintelligence is illustrated with frequency by leaders in the technology industry, and is famously depicted by Hollywood in films like Terminator, 
or more recently Ex Machina, and even the Avengers. The “furious deity A.I.” is a story you know, because it is the story you are constantly told: we build the thinking machine, 
it surpasses our abilities in every way, and it destroys us for one of any number of reasons.Maybe it perceives us as a threat. Maybe we’re just in its way, 
and it hardly perceives us at all — mankind, a disposable insect race.

There are of course many arguments in opposition to the now ubiquitous concept of our apocalypse by artificial intelligence. 
I myself have called into question the logic of such dystopian arguments in Anatomy of Next. But our subject here is less pertaining to the nature of the conscious machine than 
it is to the way we talk about this subject, and what it means. First, consider that most of the artificial intelligence depicted in culture looks human, a representation with 
no basis in technological reality. Then, the true scope of the Singularity is almost impossible to predict, which begs a question: where are these opinions about the broadly 
unknowable coming from?
